Data Analysis of Coffee Orders

Spencer Reinsfield - srei868

Using R Studio to Analyse Coffee Order Data

For this visual data story, I went the University of Aucklands Ora Cafe at the Recreation Centre and observed coffee orders. The data collected included variables such the name of the drink, the temperature of the drink, the time it took to make the drink, etc.

I was the only person involved in the data collection process.

To explore the data that was collected, I have logged the data with renamed csv file variables. The file that performs this task is data_visualisation.R

Now that this is complete, I added lots code to the end of data_visualisation.R to produce data visualisations.

What is the most common Ora Cafe Order?

This graph analyses the categorical variable drink_name by the number of observations of each drink_name.

I used geom_col() because the graph of drink_name by the number of observations of each drink_name would be much less dense than geom_bar() as there were 11 different drinks to consider in the plot.

The colouring depends on whether the drink is a black coffee or white coffee. This helps to also visualise the difference in popularity between black coffee and white coffee.

Does the Month the Data was Recorded Affect the Time it takes to Complete an Order

Made using geom_boxplot() combined with facet_wrap(vars()), this graph shows the difference in scatter between the time to make for hot drinks and cold drinks depending on the month of the year (the months the data was recorded). The box plots on the left are the data collected from Project 2 in March and the box plots on the right are the data collected for this project in May.

I coloured the hot drinks in red and the cold drinks in light blue.

I could have added geom_vline() to the plot, but the main point of this graph is not to show the mean time to complete an order, but to show whether there is a difference in the time to complete an order in March and May.

What is the Mean Time it takes to Complete an Order for Each Drink?

I used geom_jitter() combined with geom_point() to create a graph that, unlike the box plots, shows the means time to make for each drink and each observation of each drink.

It is important to bare in mind that the sample size each drink is very small, so the mean time to make for each drink is likely to be bias. Although this is true, this jitter plot made me wonder what drinks would have the longest average time to make - which brings me to the last graph.

What Coffees have the Longest Average Time to Make?

This graph visualises the top 5 highest mean time to make. Out of all the drinks within the data set, these 5 were the longest to make on average.

I made this plot using geom_col() combined with geom_text() to put the names of the drinks at the top of the bars because the names of the drinks were initially overlapping each other.

What I find interesting about this plot is that the Long Black and Americano are in the top 5 longest average time to make. I did not expect this because these drinks only require an espresso and hot water - a much easier drink to make than those that require frothing milk.
